{"title_page": "Wendy Alexander", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Wendy Alexander\n| honorific-suffix = [[Royal Society of Edinburgh|FRSE]]\n| image = Wendy Alexander.jpg\n| imagesize = 220px\n| office = [[Scottish Labour Party#Leader of the Scottish Labour Party|Leader of the Scottish Labour Party]]\n| term_start = 14 September 2007\n| term_end = 28 June 2008\n| deputy = [[Cathy Jamieson]]\n| leader = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| predecessor = [[Jack McConnell]]\n| successor = [[Iain Gray]]\n| office1 = [[Minister for Enterprise and Lifelong Learning|Minister for Enterprise, Transport and Lifelong Learning]]<ref>Enterprise and Lifelong Learning (2000\u201301)</ref>\n| term_start1 = 1 November 2000\n| term_end1 = 3 May 2002\n| firstminister1 = [[Henry McLeish]]<br>[[Jim Wallace, Baron Wallace of Tankerness|Jim Wallace]] <small>(Acting)</small><br>[[Jack McConnell]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Henry McLeish]] {{small|(Enterprise and Lifelong Learning)}}<br>[[Sarah Boyack]] {{small|(Transport and Planning)}}\n| successor1 = [[Iain Gray]]\n| office2 = [[Minister for Communities]]\n| firstminister2 = [[Donald Dewar]]<br>[[Jim Wallace, Baron Wallace of Tankerness|Jim Wallace]] <small>(Acting)</small>\n| term_start2 = 19 May 1999\n| term_end2 = 1 November 2000\n| predecessor2 = ''Office created''\n| successor2 = ''Office abolished''\n| office3 = [[Member of the Scottish Parliament]] <br> for [[Paisley North (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Paisley North]]\n| firstminister3 = \n| term_start3 = 6 May 1999\n| term_end3 = 22 March 2011\n| predecessor3 = [[Scotland Act 1998|''Constituency created'']]\n| successor3 = [[Boundary Commissions (United Kingdom)|''Constituency abolished'']]\n| office4 = \n| term_start4 = \n| term_end4 = \n| predecessor4 = \n| successor4 = \n| nationality = British\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| spouse = Prof Brian Kemp Ashcroft\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1963|6|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], Scotland, UK\n| relations = [[Douglas Alexander]] (brother)\n| children = 2\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[University of Glasgow]]<br>[[University of Warwick]]<br>[[INSEAD]]\n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Wendy Alexander''' (born 27 June 1963, [[Glasgow]]) is a retired Scottish politician and the former [[Member of the Scottish Parliament]] (MSP) for [[Paisley North (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Paisley North]]. She held various Scottish Government cabinet posts and was the leader of the [[Scottish Labour Party|Labour Party]] group in the [[Scottish Parliament]] from 2007\u20132008. In 2010\u20132011 she convened the Scotland Bill Committee on financial powers of the Scottish Parliament.\n\nAfter leaving politics, she was appointed Associate Dean of Global Business and Associate Dean for Degree Programmes and Career Services at the [[London Business School]], and in April 2015 was appointed as Vice-Principal (International) by the [[University of Dundee]].<ref>[http://www.dundee.ac.uk/news/2015/dundee-appoints-vice-principal-to-head-global-drive.php Dundee appoints Vice-Principal to head global drive, [[University of Dundee]] 24 February 2015]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dundee.ac.uk/about/staff/profile/wendy-alexander/|title=Ms Wendy Alexander|last=|first=|date=|website=University of Dundee|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024004249/https://www.dundee.ac.uk/about/staff/profile/wendy-alexander/|archive-date=2016-10-24|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In March 2016 she was elected a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Edinburgh]] for her work for the university sector.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royalsoced.org.uk/1200_2016ElectedFellows.html|title=2016 Elected Fellows|last=|first=|date=|website=Royal Society of Edinburgh|publisher=Royalsoced.org.uk|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309021343/https://www.royalsoced.org.uk/1200_2016ElectedFellows.html|archive-date=2016-03-09|accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nAlexander was born on 27 June 1963 to Dr Joyce O. Alexander and Reverend Douglas N. Alexander.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U5230|title=Who's who|last=|first=|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2017|isbn=|edition=Online|location=|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref> Alexander attended [[Park Mains High School]] in [[Erskine]] and won a scholarship to [[Lester B. Pearson College]] in British Columbia before studying at the [[University of Glasgow]], where she graduated with a [[British undergraduate degree classification|First Class]] [[Master of Arts (Scotland)|MA (Hons)]] in [[Economic History|Economic and Modern History]]. She later gained a postgraduate [[Master of Arts|MA]] in Industrial Relations from the [[University of Warwick]], and an [[MBA]] from [[INSEAD]]. She was awarded an honorary degree from [[Strathclyde University]] in 2007.\n\n==Early career==\nAfter her [[MBA]] Alexander worked for [[Booz & Co]]., an international management consultancy, undertaking assignments in Europe, Asia, North America and Australasia.\n\n===Adviser to Donald Dewar===\nFollowing Labour's landslide victory at the 1997 general election, Alexander was appointed [[Special advisers (UK government)|Special Adviser]] to [[Donald Dewar]] when he became [[Secretary of State for Scotland]]. She was deeply involved in the preparation of the White Paper on devolution, the [[Scotland Act 1998]] and preparations for the establishment of the Scottish Parliament, all matters she had published on during the 1990s.\n\n==Member of Scottish Parliament==\nWendy Alexander served as a [[Member of the Scottish Parliament]] (MSP) from its creation in 1999 until 2011.\n\n===Ministerial career===\nFrom 1999 to 2002 Wendy Alexander was a Scottish Government minister, first serving as [[Minister for Communities]], then as [[Minister for Enterprise and Lifelong Learning]], and subsequently as Minister for Enterprise, Transport and Lifelong Learning.\n\nAs Communities Minister she launched the free central heating installation programme for all pensioners without a system.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/930127.stm Fuel poverty pledge to elderly] [[BBC]], 18 September 2000</ref> She oversaw the creation of the first social justice report, \"A Scotland where everyone matters \u2013 our vision for Social Justice\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/Doc/158142/0042789.pdf |title=B10417-Social Justice text fin |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> setting ambitious new targets for delivering social justice and defeating child poverty in Scotland, and an Annual Scottish Social Justice Report to measure progress towards those targets.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/531598.stm Executive poverty pledges] [[BBC]], 22 November 1999</ref><ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/News/Releases/1999/11/e3c12f7b-132d-4f0c-8b57-e2681c088c9e A Scotland where everyone matters \u2013 our vision for social justice] Scottish Executive, 22 November 1999</ref>\n\nShe set up the Homelessness Task Force, which led to radical homelessness legislation<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/371550.stm Homeless review launched] [[BBC]], 17 June 1999</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/429398.stm Task force homes in on homelessness] [[BBC]], 25 August 1999</ref> and she championed the community ownership of housing by tenants including the removal of \u00a31.6bn of Glasgow debt.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/926954.stm Minister wants tenants in charge] [[BBC]], 16 September 2000</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/707590.stm Housing transfer moves forward] [[BBC]] 10 April 2000</ref> The tenants subsequently voted in a referendum 2:1 in favour of transfer \u2013 the largest of its kind in the UK, involving 89,000 homes.\n\nAs Communities Minister, Alexander fought hard to bring about the repeal of Section 28 to contribute to social acceptance and greater equality for the LGBT community by removing a ban on the promotion of homosexuality by local authorities.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/scottish-parliament-repeals-section-28-715651.html Scottish Parliament repeals Section 28][[Independent (newspaper)|Independent]] 22 June 2000</ref> in the face of a sustained campaign by Stagecoach millionaire and later [[Scottish National Party|SNP]] donor [[Brian Souter]] to keep the legislation. In the end the repeal, contained in the  ethical Standards in Public Life (Scotland) Bill<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scottish.parliament.uk/business/bills/billsnotInProgress/index.htm#9 |title=The Scottish Parliament: - Bills - Bills not in progress (1999 - 2003) |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101225085402/http://scottish.parliament.uk/business/bills/billsnotInProgress/index.htm#9 |archive-date=25 December 2010 }}</ref> was passed by 99 votes to 17.<ref>[http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/officialReports/meetingsParliament/or-00/or070502.htm#Col599 Official Report, 21 June 2000] [[Scottish Parliament]]</ref> During the final debate, Alexander said, \"Repeal is not, and never has been, about the promotion of homosexuality in our schools. It is not about political correctness or, even less, about marriage. It is about building a tolerant Scotland. We know that teachers are confused about the meaning of section 2A, we know that bullying exists in our schools and elsewhere, and we know that children's organisations overwhelmingly back repeal.\"<ref>[http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/officialReports/meetingsParliament/or-00/or070502.htm#Col592 Official Report, 21 June 2000] [[Scottish Parliament]]</ref>\n\nAlexander oversaw the Scottish Executive's response to the recommendations of the McIntosh Commission into the future of local government in Scotland,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/375159.stm PR for Scottish council elections][[BBC]], 22 June 1999</ref> introducing a package of measures for local government<ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/library2/doc04/ser-06.htm  Report of the Commission on Local Government and the Scottish Parliament-The Scottish Executive's Response] [[Scottish Executive]]</ref><ref>[http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/officialReports/meetingsParliament/or-99/or011305.htm Official Report, 2 July 1999] [[Scottish Parliament]]</ref> including giving local authorities the lead role in developing Community Planning, creating a formal Power of Community Initiative (later known as a power of well being) and establishing the Renewing Local Democracy (Kerley) Working Party on electoral systems.<ref>http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/Doc/158178/0042807.pdf</ref> Building on the work of the Best Value Taskforce, she also announced plans for a statutory duty to secure Best Value in local government services.<ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/News/Releases/2000/06/75d58515-7496-4727-8170-d401a4356232 Helping councils lead their communities] [[Scottish Executive]], 8 June 2000</ref>\n\nShe also published the first Equality Statement to Parliament, established the Executive's Equalities Unit,<ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/library3/social/wtem-02.asp Equality Strategy: Working together for Equality] [[Scottish Executive]]</ref><ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/News/Releases/1999/09/f8967841-74e5-4555-9cb8-bfbc6f398759 Pledge to put equality of opportunity at heart of policy making][[Scottish Executive]], 28 September 1999</ref> announced the first Scottish-wide fund to tackle violence against women \u2013 the Domestic Abuse Service Development Fund<ref>[https://www.theyworkforyou.com/sp/?gid=1999-10-27.51.2 Official Report, 27 October 1999][[Scottish Parliament]]</ref> \u2013 and the first national loan fund,<ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/News/Releases/1999/11/69f5cdda-fc63-4125-92f4-52c07923e9ee \u00a310 million fund to boost community projects] [[Scottish Executive]], 3 November 1999</ref> administered by a new organisation \u2013 Social Investment Scotland<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.socialinvestmentscotland.com/ |title=Providing Affordable Social Loan Funding |publisher=Social Investment Scotland |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> \u2013 to invest in emerging social enterprises and \"make it easier for the voluntary sector to emerge as an effective third force, alongside the traditional public and private sectors\".<ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/News/Releases/2000/03/b198ba2f-670f-4de3-b98b-5331c380a381 \u00a313 million to help communities help themselves] [[Scottish Executive]], 13 March 2000</ref><ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/News/Releases/2000/10/8b51935c-8c37-4c89-81fa-b3372438b83e Wendy Alexander Announces Extra \u00a31.2 Million For Voluntary Network Across Scotland] [[Scottish Executive]], 4 October 2000</ref>\n\nAs Enterprise Minister Alexander launched Smart, Successful Scotland,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/Doc/158455/0042945.pdf |title=Smart Scotland Cover |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> a widely welcomed new economic strategy for Scotland<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1839004.stm Firms told to go upmarket] [[BBC]], 24 February 2002</ref> supporting high-skill, high-value investment such as that by Rolls-Royce.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1943339.stm Rolls-Royce plans \u00a385m factory] [[BBC]], 22 April 2002</ref> She launched Scotland's first ever Science strategy<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/Doc/158401/0042918.pdf |title=Science Strategy 15. 8.01 |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1510717.stm Executive makes science centre-stage] [[BBC]], 27 August 2001</ref> and developed a better pipeline to get ideas out of labs and into businesses, including the Proof of Concept Fund<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1535585.stm More cash for innovators] [[BBC]], 10 September 2001</ref> and the Scottish Co-Investment Fund<ref>[http://www.scottish-enterprise.com/invest_scottish_co_investment_fund_faqs ]{{dead link|date=February 2020}}</ref> to stimulate private venture capital investment in emerging businesses.<ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/News/Releases/2003/03/3482 Scottish Co-investment Fund][[Scottish Executive]], 30 March 2003</ref> She also championed the first broadband strategy for Scotland and took action to tackle the 'digital divide'.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1158281.stm Minister's net push help plea] [[BBC]], 7 February 2001</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/631160.stm Poor lag behind IT revolution] [[BBC]], 4 February 2000</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/627633.stm Libraries book a place on the internet] [[BBC]], 7 February 2001</ref>\n\nAlexander promoted a \"learning, earning\" nation including the doubling of the number of Modern Apprenticeships,<ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/News/Releases/2000/11/23e2e05c-2cdb-4d9d-8c0b-d8f0fa19c7ff Wendy Alexander announces action plan to get every Scot job ready] [[Scottish Executive]], 30 November 2000</ref> jointly leading the Clyde Shipyards Taskforce<ref>http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/Doc/158457/0042946.pdf</ref> to help modernise shipbuilding on the Clyde through investment in skills,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1799673.stm Tide turning for Clyde shipbuilding] [[BBC]], 4 February 2002</ref> and in the face of the global downturn in electronics hitting companies such as Motorola launched what became the PACE (Partnership for Continuing Employment<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Business-Industry/support/15419 |title=Supporting business - gov.scot |publisher=Scotland.gov.uk |date=2020-01-22 |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref>) initiative to help those made redundant find work quickly. \nAs Minister with responsibility for skills and lifelong learning she promoted higher education enterprise links and championed research, modernising management<ref>[http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=165358 Polishing the Scottish jewel] Times Higher Education, 19 October 2001</ref> and widening access to universities by those previously excluded.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1031333.stm Minister targets university elitism] [[BBC]], 19 November 2000</ref> She also extended Educational Maintenance Allowances to support pupils from low income families to complete their schooling.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1243388.stm Cash for learning scheme widened] [[BBC]], 26 March 2001</ref>\n\nAlexander launched a new international economic strategy for Scotland called Global Connections<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/Doc/158429/0042932.pdf |title=B21055 strategy cover 2 up |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> realigning Scotland's international economic effort with the Smart Successful Scotland strategy,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1578716.stm Plan to 'globalise' Scotland's economy][[BBC]], 4 October 2001</ref> bringing together Scotland's previously separate inward investment and export agencies into one organisation, Scotland Development International<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sdi.co.uk/ |title=Scottish Development International |publisher=SDI |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref><ref>[http://business.scotsman.com/thescotsmaneconomicdebate/Wendy-Alexander-Putting-the-enterprise.2302734.jp Wendy Alexander: Putting the enterprise into higher education] Scotsman, 15 February 2002</ref> and created the Globalscot network<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalscot.com/ |title=The global business network committed to helping Scottish businesses succeed |publisher=GlobalScot |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> to develop and expand Scotland's standing in the global business community.\n\nAlexander resigned from ministerial office on 4 May 2002. After her resignation from [[Jack McConnell]]'s Cabinet she became a visiting professor at the [[Strathclyde Business School]] and became a member, and subsequently Chair of the Scottish Parliament's Finance Committee. She inspired and led the Allander Series of seminars which had the aim of encouraging fresh thinking on Scotland's economic future.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/3157594.stm Overseas threat to economy] [[BBC]] 2 October 2003</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/3475443.stm Single city call for central belt] [[BBC]] 10 February 2004</ref> The seminars brought William Baumol, Ed Glaeser and Nobel laureates James Heckman and Paul Krugman from across the spectrum of political economy to Scotland to reflect on issues such as the returns to early intervention, supporting innovation and cities as future growth engines.<ref>[http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/seeds-of-allander-have-fallen-on-fertile-ground-1.81874 Seeds of Allander have fallen on fertile ground] Herald, 29 June 2004</ref><ref>[http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/opinion/Positive-ideas-for-Scotland.2541483.jp Positive ideas for Scotland] Scotsman, 29 June 2004</ref>\n\nShe also authored ''Chasing the Tartan Tiger: Lessons from a Celtic Cousin?'' (2003),<ref>[http://www.smith-institute.org.uk/smith-engine/_filesmgr/File/ChasingtheTartanTigerLessonsfromaCelticcousin.pdf ]{{dead link|date=February 2020}}</ref> co-edited (with Diane Coyle and Brian Ashcroft) ''New Wealth for Old Nations: Scotland\u2019s Economic Prospects'' (2005),<ref>[http://press.princeton.edu/chapters/i7949.html ]{{dead link|date=February 2020}}</ref><ref>[http://scotlandonsunday.scotsman.com/business/Strength-in-numbers.2628546.jp Strength in numbers] Scotland on Sunday, 22 May 2005</ref> edited an anthology of essays on the life of the late First Minister, Donald Dewar: ''Scotland's first First Minister'' (2005)<ref>http://www.rbooks.co.uk/product.aspx?id=1845960386 </ref> and wrote a non-political column for young mums in the ''[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]''.\n\n==Leader of Scottish Labour==\n\n===Election===\nFollowing the [[2007 Scottish Parliament election|Scottish Parliament elections in May 2007]], Alexander became Shadow [[Cabinet Secretary for Finance and Sustainable Growth]]. Following [[Jack McConnell]]'s resignation in August 2007, she announced her candidacy for Leader of Labour in the Scottish Parliament. Alexander laid out her vision to \"Renew the party organisation, reform the policies, and reconnect Scottish Labour with its electorate\".<ref>[http://www.wendyalexander.co.uk/speeches/wendy-alexander-candidate-for-scottish-labour-goup-leader-launch-speech/ Candidate Launch Speech] wendyalexander.co.uk</ref> Other contenders ruled themselves out and she was elected unopposed by Labour MSPs on 14 September 2007.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/6993828.stm Alexander leads Scottish labour], ''[[BBC News Online]]'', 14 September 2007</ref>\n\nAs Scottish Labour leader Alexander believed that \"the people of Scotland told us loud and clear they wanted change. They didn't whisper \u2013 they shouted it. So change we must!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-12496030 |title=A look at former Scottish Labour leader Wendy Alexander |publisher=BBC News |date=2011-02-17 |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> She argued that Labour must offer radical change to regain the trust of voters, a vision spelt out in ''Scottish Labour New Directions: Change is what we do'',<ref>http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/pdfs/21_03_08_wendy.pdf</ref> a publication outlining her views on the future policy direction for Scottish Labour.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7307371.stm Labour must show radical change] [[BBC]], 23 March 2008</ref> Addressing Labour's Scottish Conference as Leader she spoke of the need for Labour to be the progressive party of Scotland. Alexander argued: \"'Scotland' is not a political philosophy. 'Scotland' can just as easily be [[Adam Smith]] as it can be [[John Smith (Labour Party leader)|John Smith]]. The world over, politics comes down to a choice: right versus left, conservatives versus progressives, nationalists versus internationalists\".<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7319850.stm Alexander says fightback begins] [[BBC]], 29 March 2008</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/pdfs/31_03_08_wendyspeech.pdf Speech to Scottish Conference by Wendy Alexander] [[BBC]], 29 March 2008</ref>\n\nOrganisationally, she called for a new approach to candidate selection, including primary systems to give all Labour supporters a chance to be involved in choosing their local member. Policy initiatives included establishing a Literacy Commission with [[Rhona Brankin]] to investigate child literacy standards in [[Scottish schools]]<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2008/jun/24/schools.education Rebus creator turns government inspector] Guardian, 24 June 2008</ref> (subsequently embraced by all parties in the Parliament),<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/8393805.stm Fifth of Scots have poor literacy] [[BBC]], 4 December 2009</ref> supporting investment in the early years, including nursery places for all vulnerable 2-year-olds, more one-on-one tuition in schools, personalised care plans for those with chronic conditions and legislation providing for a modern apprenticeship for every qualified school leaver who sought one.\n\n===Calman Commission===\n{{main|Calman Commission|Scotland Bill (2011)}}\n\nAlexander made a speech at the [[University of Edinburgh]] on [[St Andrew's Day]] 2007 in which she set out the case for a wide-ranging review of the [[Devolution in the United Kingdom|devolution settlement]], with a view to identifying possible areas for reform.<ref>[http://www.institute-of-governance.org/news-events/news/2007/wendy_alexander_presents_a_new_agenda_for_scotland Wendy Alexander presents A New Agenda for Scotland][http://www.institute-of-governance.org/ Institute of Governance]</ref> The speech laid out her proposals for \"a more balanced [[home rule]] package\" including greater financial [[accountability]] and new tax powers for the [[Scottish Parliament]] (a cause that she had first championed when she led the Allander Series) in order that the \"Union become a more comfortable home for all its members\".<ref>[http://www.heraldscotland.com/alexander-calls-for-tax-powers-to-replace-the-barnett-formula-1.844478 Alexander calls for tax powers to replace the Barnett formula] Herald, 1 December 2007</ref> She said \"Scotland wants to see a future that allows her to walk taller within the UK without walking out\" and called for a new \"expert-led and independent\" Scottish constitutional commission.\n\nAs Labour leader in the Scottish Parliament, she set this in motion by working with the Conservative and Liberal Democrat leaders to set up the [[Commission on Scottish Devolution]] (aka the Calman Commission) in a \"bold cross-party, cross-border initiative\".<ref>[http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/news/Parties-join-forces-to-bulldoze.3587865.jp Parties join forces to bulldoze SNP] Scotsman, 7 December 2007</ref><ref>[http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/politics/it-s-all-part-of-the-process-1.870431 Its all part of the process] Herald, 7 December 2007</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7709850.stm Devolution body to take evidence] [[BBC]]</ref> The review was established by a vote of the Scottish Parliament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7129899.stm |title=MSPs back devolution review body |publisher=BBC News |date=2007-12-06 |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> The Calman Commission became a unique Scottish Parliament-UK Government joint venture which reported back to the Parliament in June 2009 proposing wide-ranging changes in the financing of the Scottish Parliament.<ref>[http://www.commissiononscottishdevolution.org.uk/uploads/2009-06-12-csd-final-report-2009fbookmarked.pdf Serving Scotland Better][[Commission on Scottish Devolution]], June 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.commissiononscottishdevolution.org.uk/uploads/2009-06-12-csd-a5_final-summary_ibook.pdf Serving Scotland Better Executive Summary][[Commission on Scottish Devolution]], June 2009</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/8100215.stm Digesting the Calman report calls] [[BBC]]</ref> Alexander wrote then \"history teaches that constitutional reform has never been gifted to Scotland. It has to be fought and argued for... Calman will shape the next phase of Scotland's journey\u2026[with] a range of common sense measures to improve relationships\".<ref>[http://scotlandonsunday.scotsman.com/opinion/Wendy-Alexander-Blueprint-for-the.5364025.jp Wendy Alexander: Blueprint for the future of Scotland] Scotland on Sunday, 14 June 2009</ref>\n\nOn St. Andrew's Day 2010, three years to the day after Alexander's call for a Commission, the UK Government introduced a new Scotland Bill. The proposals in the bill closely followed the Commission's recommendations and proposed major new financial powers worth \u00a312 billion, giving Holyrood control of a third of its budget. Under the legislation, Holyrood will set a Scottish income tax rate each year from 2015, applying equally to the basic, high and additional rates. The UK Government called it the \"biggest transfer of fiscal powers to Scotland since the creation of the Union.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Brian Taylor |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-11863388 |title=Holyrood to get new budget powers under Scotland Bill |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> In December 2010 Alexander was appointed convener of the Scottish Parliament's Committee to report on the bill.\n\n===Scottish independence referendum===\n{{main|Referendum (Scotland) Bill, 2010}}\n\nDuring a TV interview on 4 May 2008, Wendy Alexander suggested that she would be willing to support a [[referendum]] on [[Scottish Independence]] saying \"Bring it on!\". It was a bold move, but led to suggestions of a rift between her and the prime minister, who did not overtly back her.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-12496030 |title=A look a former Scottish Labour leader Wendy Alexander |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2011-02-17 |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> On 7 May, at [[Prime Minister's Questions]], Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]] stated that she was not, in fact, offering Labour's support for an immediate referendum.<ref>[http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/latestnews/Labour-implodes-over-independence-vote.4061348.jp Labour implodes over independence vote][[The Scotsman]], 8 May 2008</ref>\n\nDuring [[First Minister's Questions]] in the Scottish Parliament, on 8 May, Alexander asked Alex Salmond to bring forward a referendum bill at the first opportunity. [[Alex Salmond]] declined the offer of Labour support for a referendum, preferring to delay by at least a further year, saying \"We will stick to what was laid out in pages 8 and 15 of the SNP manifesto\".<ref>[http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/officialReports/meetingsParliament/or-08/sor0508-02.htm#Col8425 Official Report, 8 May 2008][[Scottish Parliament]]</ref>\n\n== Resignation over foreign donation==\n{{main|Labour party proxy and undeclared donations (2007)}}\n\nIn 2007, a controversy developed after it emerged that Alexander's campaign team had accepted a \u00a3950 impermissible donation from Paul Green, a property magnate,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7479025.stm Q&A: Wendy Alexander donations row ], ''[[BBC]]'', 1 December 2007</ref> a matter that was investigated by the [[Electoral Commission (United Kingdom)|Electoral Commission]] and [[Strathclyde Police]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/7120096.stm Alexander wrote to illegal donor], ''[[BBC News Online]]'', 30 November 2007</ref> When it emerged that the donation of \u00a3950 had come from a personal account, and not a business account, the money was immediately forfeited. Further newspaper reports on 30 November indicated Alexander was aware of the identity of the donor, after having sent a personal letter of gratitude to Mr Green (at his home in [[Jersey]]) concerning the donation.<ref>[http://www.scotsman.com/politics/Bombshell-for-Labour-on-illegal.3585975.jp Bombshell for Labour on illegal donations], ''[[The Scotsman]]'', 1 December 2007</ref> As Mr Green was not registered as an elector in the United Kingdom this barred him from donating to a UK-based party. However, the Electoral Commission concluded in February 2008 that Alexander had taken 'significant steps' to comply with funding regulations and decided there was no basis for further action.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7232516.stm Alexander in clear over donations], ''[[BBC News Online]]'', 7 February 2008</ref> As part of the Electoral Commission ruling, they also stated that Alexander \"did not take all reasonable steps\" and that \"there is not sufficient evidence to establish that an offence has been committed\".<ref>[http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/news-and-media/news-releases/electoral-commission-media-centre/news-releases-donations/statement-by-the-electoral-commission Statement by the Electoral Commission], ''[[Electoral Commission (United Kingdom)|Electoral Commission]]'', 7 February 2008</ref>\nThese mixed messages have resulted in a number of people questioning the decision, including [[Alex Salmond]] the head of the [[Scottish Government]] who likened the result to a ''[[not proven]]'' verdict.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7232516.stm Alexander in clear over donation], ''[[BBC News Online]]'', 7 February 2008</ref>\n\nIn a separate development, a few days earlier in February 2008, the Scottish Parliament standards watchdog reported Alexander to the [[procurator fiscal]] for failing to declare as gifts the donations that were made to the fund for her campaign for the Scottish Labour Party leadership.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7224739.stm Alexander reported over donations], ''[[BBC News Online]]'', 3 February 2008</ref> Alexander had been told by the parliamentary authorities that there was no need to declare these donations as gifts.<ref name=\"Labour leader faces one-day ban\"/> In previous leadership campaigns, campaign donations were not treated as gifts. Again the subsequent investigation led to a decision by the [[Crown Office and Procurator Fiscal Service|Crown Office]] to take no further action.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7281820.stm |title=Alexander will not be prosecuted |publisher=BBC News |date=2008-03-06 |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\nDespite this ruling, on 26 June 2008, on the eve of the Parliamentary summer recess, the SNP-led Standards Committee of the Parliament voted 4 to 3 to propose a one-day ban from the Scottish Parliament<ref name=\"Labour leader faces one-day ban\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7474475.stm |title=Labour leader faces one-day ban |publisher=BBC News |date=2008-06-26 |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> as a sanction for not declaring leadership campaign donations as gifts on the Parliament's register of interests. The proposed ban was overwhelmingly rejected by the Parliament in a subsequent vote in September 2008.<ref>[http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/officialReports/meetingsParliament/or-08/sor0904-02.htm#Col10577 Official Report, Decision Time, 4 September 2008] [[Scottish Parliament]]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7596764.stm |title=MSPs vote against Alexander ban |publisher=BBC News |date=2008-09-04 |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> However, with Holyrood going into summer recess at the time, Alexander would have had to wait until September for all MSPs to vote on the recommendation. So, rather than having the issue hanging over her \u2013 and her party \u2013 Alexander announced her resignation as leader on 28 June 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-12496030 |title=A look at former Scottish Labour leader Wendy Alexander |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2011-02-17 |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> She subsequently stated it had been a mistake for her to take on the leadership of Scottish Labour while her children were so young.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-12496625 |title=Wendy Alexander to quit Scots parliament at election |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nFrom 2008\u20132011 Alexander served as a member of the [[Committees of the Scottish Parliament|Scottish Parliament's Economy, Energy and Tourism Committee]]. She was also convenor of the [[Scotland Bill 2011|Scotland Bill]] Committee, which produced the report for the Scottish Parliament and UK Government in March 2011 proposing [[devolution|new powers]] for the [[Scottish Parliament]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Brian Taylor |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-12621048 |title=MSPs call for more Holyrood power under Scotland Bill |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> Many of these proposals recommend greater [[fiscal autonomy for Scotland]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.scotsman.com/news/The-Wendy-Alexander-plan-aims.6728210.jp |title=The Wendy Alexander plan aims to bridge gap in nation's finances |publisher=News.scotsman.com |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> including improved borrowing powers, the ability to issue bonds and further tax devolution.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-11863392 |title=Q&A: Scotland Bill |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2010-11-30 |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> Despite the Scottish Government's initial opposition to the bill they supported the Scotland Bill Committee's recommendations, with parliament voting 121:3 in favour. In her valedictory speech on the Scotland Bill, Alexander said: \"This initiative has from beginning to end been cross-party, consensual and co-operative among the participating parties. [...] The bill will deliver the most far-reaching transfer of financial powers from London since the creation of the union. [...] In the future, all Scottish political parties will have to make decisions about raising money as well as about spending it. [...] The bill serves Scotland better [...] It is, quite simply, in the national interest.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/apps2/business/orsearch/ReportView.aspx?r=6175&mode=html |title=Official Report \u2013 Meeting of the Parliament 10 March 2011 |publisher=Scottish.parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\nShe stood down from Parliament in May 2011 to seek a new life outside active politics.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-12496030 |title=A Look at former Scottish Labour leader Wendy Alexander |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2011-02-17 |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\nAlexander also serves as a member of the [[Social Market Foundation]]'s Advisory Board and [[Reform Scotland]]'s Political Advisory Board.\n\n==Personal life and family==\nWendy Alexander is married to Professor Brian Ashcroft and has [[Twin|fraternal twin]] children.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAlexander's brother [[Douglas Alexander|Douglas]], was the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] Member of Parliament for [[Paisley and Renfrewshire South (UK Parliament constituency)|Paisley and Renfrewshire South]] and was previously [[Secretary of State for International Development]] and [[Secretary of State for Scotland]]. He served as Shadow Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs under Labour Party Leader [[Ed Miliband]], and lost his seat at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] to 20-year old [[Mhairi Black]] of the [[Scottish National Party|SNP]].\n\nAlexander supports [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers FC]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/rangers-celebrity-supporters-out-in-force-976295|title=Rangers' celebrity supporters out in force for UEFA Cup final|work=Daily Record|date=3 May 2008|accessdate=3 May 2008|location=Glasgow|first=John|last=Ferguson}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Scottish Executive Ministerial Teams]]\n* [[Scotland Bill 2010-11]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/msp/membersPages/wendy_alexander/index.htm Scottish Parliament biography]\n*[http://www.wendyalexandermsp.org.uk/ Wendy Alexander MSP]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par | sct}}\n|-\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency created }}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Member of the Scottish Parliament]] for [[Paisley North (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Paisley North]] | years=[[1999 Scottish Parliament election|1999]]\u20132011 }}\n{{s-after|after=Constituency abolished}}\n{{s-off}}\n|-\n{{s-non | reason = Office created }}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Minister for Communities and Sport|Minister for Communities]] | years = 1999\u20132000 }}\n{{s-non | reason = Office abolished }}\n|-\n{{s-bef | before = [[Henry McLeish]] }}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[Minister for Enterprise and Lifelong Learning]] | years=2000\u20132001 }}\n{{s-non | reason = Office abolished }}\n|-\n{{s-non | reason = Office created }}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[Minister for Enterprise and Lifelong Learning|Minister for Enterprise, Transport and Lifelong Learning]] | years = 2001\u20132002 }}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Iain Gray]] }}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Jack McConnell]] }}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Scottish Labour Party|Leader of Labour in the Scottish Parliament]] | years=2007\u20132008 }}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Iain Gray]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Scottish Labour Party}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alexander, Wendy}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Labour MSPs]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Scottish Labour Party]]\n[[Category:Scottish columnists]]\n[[Category:Scottish special advisers]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) officials]]\n[[Category:British consultants]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Scottish Parliament]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Strathclyde]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Warwick]]\n[[Category:INSEAD alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the Scottish Parliament 1999\u20132003]]\n[[Category:Members of the Scottish Parliament 2003\u20132007]]\n[[Category:Members of the Scottish Parliament 2007\u20132011]]\n[[Category:People educated at Park Mains High School]]\n[[Category:People associated with the University of Dundee]]\n[[Category:Ministers of the Scottish Government]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Scottish Government]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:Women columnists]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Wendy Alexander\n| honorific-suffix = [[Royal Society of Edinburgh|FRSE]]\n| image = Wendy Alexander.jpg\n| imagesize = 220px\n| office = [[Scottish Labour Party#Leader of the Scottish Labour Party|Leader of the Scottish Labour Party]]\n| term_start = 14 September 2007\n| term_end = 28 June 2008\n| deputy = [[Cathy Jamieson]]\n| leader = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| predecessor = [[Jack McConnell]]\n| successor = [[Iain Gray]]\n| office1 = [[Minister for Enterprise and Lifelong Learning|Minister for Enterprise, Transport and Lifelong Learning]]<ref>Enterprise and Lifelong Learning (2000\u201301)</ref>\n| term_start1 = 1 November 2000\n| term_end1 = 3 May 2002\n| firstminister1 = [[Henry McLeish]]<br>[[Jim Wallace, Baron Wallace of Tankerness|Jim Wallace]] <small>(Acting)</small><br>[[Jack McConnell]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Henry McLeish]] {{small|(Enterprise and Lifelong Learning)}}<br>[[Sarah Boyack]] {{small|(Transport and Planning)}}\n| successor1 = [[Iain Gray]]\n| office2 = [[Minister for Communities]]\n| firstminister2 = [[Donald Dewar]]<br>[[Jim Wallace, Baron Wallace of Tankerness|Jim Wallace]] <small>(Acting)</small>\n| term_start2 = 19 May 1999\n| term_end2 = 1 November 2000\n| predecessor2 = ''Office created''\n| successor2 = ''Office abolished''\n| office3 = [[Member of the Scottish Parliament]] <br> for [[Paisley North (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Paisley North]]\n| firstminister3 = \n| term_start3 = 6 May 1999\n| term_end3 = 22 March 2011\n| predecessor3 = [[Scotland Act 1998|''Constituency created'']]\n| successor3 = [[Boundary Commissions (United Kingdom)|''Constituency abolished'']]\n| office4 = \n| term_start4 = \n| term_end4 = \n| predecessor4 = \n| successor4 = \n| nationality = British\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| spouse = Prof Brian Kemp Ashcroft\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1963|6|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], Scotland, UK\n| relations = [[Douglas Alexander]] (brother)\n| children = 2\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[University of Glasgow]]<br>[[University of Warwick]]<br>[[INSEAD]]\n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Wendy Alexander''' (born 27 June 1963, [[Glasgow]]) is a retired Scottish politician and the former [[Member of the Scottish Parliament]] (MSP) for [[Paisley North (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Paisley North]]. She held various Scottish Government cabinet posts and was the leader of the [[Scottish Labour Party|Labour Party]] group in the [[Scottish Parliament]] from 2007\u20132008. In 2010\u20132011 she convened the Scotland Bill Committee on financial powers of the Scottish Parliament.\n\nAfter leaving politics, she was appointed Associate Dean of Global Business and Associate Dean for Degree Programmes and Career Services at the [[London Business School]], and in April 2015 was appointed as Vice-Principal (International) by the [[University of Dundee]].<ref>[http://www.dundee.ac.uk/news/2015/dundee-appoints-vice-principal-to-head-global-drive.php Dundee appoints Vice-Principal to head global drive, [[University of Dundee]] 24 February 2015]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dundee.ac.uk/about/staff/profile/wendy-alexander/|title=Ms Wendy Alexander|last=|first=|date=|website=University of Dundee|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024004249/https://www.dundee.ac.uk/about/staff/profile/wendy-alexander/|archive-date=2016-10-24|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref> In March 2016 she was elected a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Edinburgh]] for her work for the university sector.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royalsoced.org.uk/1200_2016ElectedFellows.html|title=2016 Elected Fellows|last=|first=|date=|website=Royal Society of Edinburgh|publisher=Royalsoced.org.uk|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309021343/https://www.royalsoced.org.uk/1200_2016ElectedFellows.html|archive-date=2016-03-09|accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nAlexander was born on 27 June 1963 to Dr Joyce O. Alexander and Reverend Douglas N. Alexander.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U5230|title=Who's who|last=|first=|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2017|isbn=|edition=Online|location=|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref> Alexander attended [[Park Mains High School]] in [[Erskine]] and won a scholarship to [[Lester B. Pearson College]] in British Columbia before studying at the [[University of Glasgow]], where she graduated with a [[British undergraduate degree classification|First Class]] [[Master of Arts (Scotland)|MA (Hons)]] in [[Economic History|Economic and Modern History]]. She later gained a postgraduate [[Master of Arts|MA]] in Industrial Relations from the [[University of Warwick]], and an [[MBA]] from [[INSEAD]]. She was awarded an honorary degree from [[Strathclyde University]] in 2007.\n\n==Early career==\nAfter her [[MBA]] Alexander worked for [[Booz & Co]]., an international management consultancy, undertaking assignments in Europe, Asia, North America and Australasia.\n\n===Adviser to Donald Dewar===\nFollowing Labour's landslide victory at the 1997 general election, Alexander was appointed [[Special advisers (UK government)|Special Adviser]] to [[Donald Dewar]] when he became [[Secretary of State for Scotland]]. She was deeply involved in the preparation of the White Paper on devolution, the [[Scotland Act 1998]] and preparations for the establishment of the Scottish Parliament, all matters she had published on during the 1990s.\n\n==Member of Scottish Parliament==\nWendy Alexander served as a [[Member of the Scottish Parliament]] (MSP) from its creation in 1999 until 2011.\n\n===Ministerial career===\nFrom 1999 to 2002 Wendy Alexander was a Scottish Government minister, first serving as [[Minister for Communities]], then as [[Minister for Enterprise and Lifelong Learning]], and subsequently as Minister for Enterprise, Transport and Lifelong Learning.\n\nAs Communities Minister she launched the free central heating installation programme for all pensioners without a system.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/930127.stm Fuel poverty pledge to elderly] [[BBC]], 18 September 2000</ref> She oversaw the creation of the first social justice report, \"A Scotland where everyone matters \u2013 our vision for Social Justice\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/Doc/158142/0042789.pdf |title=B10417-Social Justice text fin |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> setting ambitious new targets for delivering social justice and defeating child poverty in Scotland, and an Annual Scottish Social Justice Report to measure progress towards those targets.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/531598.stm Executive poverty pledges] [[BBC]], 22 November 1999</ref><ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/News/Releases/1999/11/e3c12f7b-132d-4f0c-8b57-e2681c088c9e A Scotland where everyone matters \u2013 our vision for social justice] Scottish Executive, 22 November 1999</ref>\n\nShe set up the Homelessness Task Force, which led to radical homelessness legislation<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/371550.stm Homeless review launched] [[BBC]], 17 June 1999</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/429398.stm Task force homes in on homelessness] [[BBC]], 25 August 1999</ref> and she championed the community ownership of housing by tenants including the removal of \u00a31.6bn of Glasgow debt.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/926954.stm Minister wants tenants in charge] [[BBC]], 16 September 2000</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/707590.stm Housing transfer moves forward] [[BBC]] 10 April 2000</ref> The tenants subsequently voted in a referendum 2:1 in favour of transfer \u2013 the largest of its kind in the UK, involving 89,000 homes.\n\nAs Communities Minister, Alexander fought hard to bring about the repeal of Section 28 to contribute to social acceptance and greater equality for the LGBT community by removing a ban on the promotion of homosexuality by local authorities.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/scottish-parliament-repeals-section-28-715651.html Scottish Parliament repeals Section 28][[Independent (newspaper)|Independent]] 22 June 2000</ref> in the face of a sustained campaign by Stagecoach millionaire and later [[Scottish National Party|SNP]] donor [[Brian Souter]] to keep the legislation. In the end the repeal, contained in the  ethical Standards in Public Life (Scotland) Bill<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scottish.parliament.uk/business/bills/billsnotInProgress/index.htm#9 |title=The Scottish Parliament: - Bills - Bills not in progress (1999 - 2003) |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101225085402/http://scottish.parliament.uk/business/bills/billsnotInProgress/index.htm#9 |archive-date=25 December 2010 }}</ref> was passed by 99 votes to 17.<ref>[http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/officialReports/meetingsParliament/or-00/or070502.htm#Col599 Official Report, 21 June 2000] [[Scottish Parliament]]</ref> During the final debate, Alexander said, \"Repeal is not, and never has been, about the promotion of homosexuality in our schools. It is not about political correctness or, even less, about marriage. It is about building a tolerant Scotland. We know that teachers are confused about the meaning of section 2A, we know that bullying exists in our schools and elsewhere, and we know that children's organisations overwhelmingly back repeal.\"<ref>[http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/officialReports/meetingsParliament/or-00/or070502.htm#Col592 Official Report, 21 June 2000] [[Scottish Parliament]]</ref>\n\nAlexander oversaw the Scottish Executive's response to the recommendations of the McIntosh Commission into the future of local government in Scotland,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/375159.stm PR for Scottish council elections][[BBC]], 22 June 1999</ref> introducing a package of measures for local government<ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/library2/doc04/ser-06.htm  Report of the Commission on Local Government and the Scottish Parliament-The Scottish Executive's Response] [[Scottish Executive]]</ref><ref>[http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/officialReports/meetingsParliament/or-99/or011305.htm Official Report, 2 July 1999] [[Scottish Parliament]]</ref> including giving local authorities the lead role in developing Community Planning, creating a formal Power of Community Initiative (later known as a power of well being) and establishing the Renewing Local Democracy (Kerley) Working Party on electoral systems.<ref>http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/Doc/158178/0042807.pdf</ref> Building on the work of the Best Value Taskforce, she also announced plans for a statutory duty to secure Best Value in local government services.<ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/News/Releases/2000/06/75d58515-7496-4727-8170-d401a4356232 Helping councils lead their communities] [[Scottish Executive]], 8 June 2000</ref>\n\nShe also published the first Equality Statement to Parliament, established the Executive's Equalities Unit,<ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/library3/social/wtem-02.asp Equality Strategy: Working together for Equality] [[Scottish Executive]]</ref><ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/News/Releases/1999/09/f8967841-74e5-4555-9cb8-bfbc6f398759 Pledge to put equality of opportunity at heart of policy making][[Scottish Executive]], 28 September 1999</ref> announced the first Scottish-wide fund to tackle violence against women \u2013 the Domestic Abuse Service Development Fund<ref>[https://www.theyworkforyou.com/sp/?gid=1999-10-27.51.2 Official Report, 27 October 1999][[Scottish Parliament]]</ref> \u2013 and the first national loan fund,<ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/News/Releases/1999/11/69f5cdda-fc63-4125-92f4-52c07923e9ee \u00a310 million fund to boost community projects] [[Scottish Executive]], 3 November 1999</ref> administered by a new organisation \u2013 Social Investment Scotland<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.socialinvestmentscotland.com/ |title=Providing Affordable Social Loan Funding |publisher=Social Investment Scotland |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> \u2013 to invest in emerging social enterprises and \"make it easier for the voluntary sector to emerge as an effective third force, alongside the traditional public and private sectors\".<ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/News/Releases/2000/03/b198ba2f-670f-4de3-b98b-5331c380a381 \u00a313 million to help communities help themselves] [[Scottish Executive]], 13 March 2000</ref><ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/News/Releases/2000/10/8b51935c-8c37-4c89-81fa-b3372438b83e Wendy Alexander Announces Extra \u00a31.2 Million For Voluntary Network Across Scotland] [[Scottish Executive]], 4 October 2000</ref>\n\nAs Enterprise Minister Alexander launched Smart, Successful Scotland,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/Doc/158455/0042945.pdf |title=Smart Scotland Cover |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> a widely welcomed new economic strategy for Scotland<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1839004.stm Firms told to go upmarket] [[BBC]], 24 February 2002</ref> supporting high-skill, high-value investment such as that by Rolls-Royce.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1943339.stm Rolls-Royce plans \u00a385m factory] [[BBC]], 22 April 2002</ref> She launched Scotland's first ever Science strategy<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/Doc/158401/0042918.pdf |title=Science Strategy 15. 8.01 |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1510717.stm Executive makes science centre-stage] [[BBC]], 27 August 2001</ref> and developed a better pipeline to get ideas out of labs and into businesses, including the Proof of Concept Fund<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1535585.stm More cash for innovators] [[BBC]], 10 September 2001</ref> and the Scottish Co-Investment Fund<ref>[http://www.scottish-enterprise.com/invest_scottish_co_investment_fund_faqs ]{{dead link|date=February 2020}}</ref> to stimulate private venture capital investment in emerging businesses.<ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/News/Releases/2003/03/3482 Scottish Co-investment Fund][[Scottish Executive]], 30 March 2003</ref> She also championed the first broadband strategy for Scotland and took action to tackle the 'digital divide'.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1158281.stm Minister's net push help plea] [[BBC]], 7 February 2001</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/631160.stm Poor lag behind IT revolution] [[BBC]], 4 February 2000</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/627633.stm Libraries book a place on the internet] [[BBC]], 7 February 2001</ref>\n\nAlexander promoted a \"learning, earning\" nation including the doubling of the number of Modern Apprenticeships,<ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/News/Releases/2000/11/23e2e05c-2cdb-4d9d-8c0b-d8f0fa19c7ff Wendy Alexander announces action plan to get every Scot job ready] [[Scottish Executive]], 30 November 2000</ref> jointly leading the Clyde Shipyards Taskforce<ref>http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/Doc/158457/0042946.pdf</ref> to help modernise shipbuilding on the Clyde through investment in skills,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1799673.stm Tide turning for Clyde shipbuilding] [[BBC]], 4 February 2002</ref> and in the face of the global downturn in electronics hitting companies such as Motorola launched what became the PACE (Partnership for Continuing Employment<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Business-Industry/support/15419 |title=Supporting business - gov.scot |publisher=Scotland.gov.uk |date=2020-01-22 |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref>) initiative to help those made redundant find work quickly. \nAs Minister with responsibility for skills and lifelong learning she promoted higher education enterprise links and championed research, modernising management<ref>[http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=165358 Polishing the Scottish jewel] Times Higher Education, 19 October 2001</ref> and widening access to universities by those previously excluded.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1031333.stm Minister targets university elitism] [[BBC]], 19 November 2000</ref> She also extended Educational Maintenance Allowances to support pupils from low income families to complete their schooling.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1243388.stm Cash for learning scheme widened] [[BBC]], 26 March 2001</ref>\n\nAlexander launched a new international economic strategy for Scotland called Global Connections<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/Doc/158429/0042932.pdf |title=B21055 strategy cover 2 up |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> realigning Scotland's international economic effort with the Smart Successful Scotland strategy,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1578716.stm Plan to 'globalise' Scotland's economy][[BBC]], 4 October 2001</ref> bringing together Scotland's previously separate inward investment and export agencies into one organisation, Scotland Development International<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sdi.co.uk/ |title=Scottish Development International |publisher=SDI |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref><ref>[http://business.scotsman.com/thescotsmaneconomicdebate/Wendy-Alexander-Putting-the-enterprise.2302734.jp Wendy Alexander: Putting the enterprise into higher education] Scotsman, 15 February 2002</ref> and created the Globalscot network<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalscot.com/ |title=The global business network committed to helping Scottish businesses succeed |publisher=GlobalScot |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> to develop and expand Scotland's standing in the global business community.\n\nAlexander resigned from ministerial office on 4 May 2002. After her resignation from [[Jack McConnell]]'s Cabinet she became a visiting professor at the [[Strathclyde Business School]] and became a member, and subsequently Chair of the Scottish Parliament's Finance Committee. She inspired and led the Allander Series of seminars which had the aim of encouraging fresh thinking on Scotland's economic future.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/3157594.stm Overseas threat to economy] [[BBC]] 2 October 2003</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/3475443.stm Single city call for central belt] [[BBC]] 10 February 2004</ref> The seminars brought William Baumol, Ed Glaeser and Nobel laureates James Heckman and Paul Krugman from across the spectrum of political economy to Scotland to reflect on issues such as the returns to early intervention, supporting innovation and cities as future growth engines.<ref>[http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/seeds-of-allander-have-fallen-on-fertile-ground-1.81874 Seeds of Allander have fallen on fertile ground] Herald, 29 June 2004</ref><ref>[http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/opinion/Positive-ideas-for-Scotland.2541483.jp Positive ideas for Scotland] Scotsman, 29 June 2004</ref>\n\nShe also authored ''Chasing the Tartan Tiger: Lessons from a Celtic Cousin?'' (2003),<ref>[http://www.smith-institute.org.uk/smith-engine/_filesmgr/File/ChasingtheTartanTigerLessonsfromaCelticcousin.pdf ]{{dead link|date=February 2020}}</ref> co-edited (with Diane Coyle and Brian Ashcroft) ''New Wealth for Old Nations: Scotland\u2019s Economic Prospects'' (2005),<ref>[http://press.princeton.edu/chapters/i7949.html ]{{dead link|date=February 2020}}</ref><ref>[http://scotlandonsunday.scotsman.com/business/Strength-in-numbers.2628546.jp Strength in numbers] Scotland on Sunday, 22 May 2005</ref> edited an anthology of essays on the life of the late First Minister, Donald Dewar: ''Scotland's first First Minister'' (2005)<ref>http://www.rbooks.co.uk/product.aspx?id=1845960386 </ref> and wrote a non-political column for young mums in the ''[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]''.\n\n==Leader of Scottish Labour==\n\n===Election===\nFollowing the [[2007 Scottish Parliament election|Scottish Parliament elections in May 2007]], Alexander became Shadow [[Cabinet Secretary for Finance and Sustainable Growth]]. Following [[Jack McConnell]]'s resignation in August 2007, she announced her candidacy for Leader of Labour in the Scottish Parliament. Alexander laid out her vision to \"Renew the party organisation, reform the policies, and reconnect Scottish Labour with its electorate\".<ref>[http://www.wendyalexander.co.uk/speeches/wendy-alexander-candidate-for-scottish-labour-goup-leader-launch-speech/ Candidate Launch Speech] wendyalexander.co.uk</ref> Other contenders ruled themselves out and she was elected unopposed by Labour MSPs on 14 September 2007.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/6993828.stm Alexander leads Scottish labour], ''[[BBC News Online]]'', 14 September 2007</ref>\n\nAs Scottish Labour leader Alexander believed that \"the people of Scotland told us loud and clear they wanted change. They didn't whisper \u2013 they shouted it. So change we must!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-12496030 |title=A look at former Scottish Labour leader Wendy Alexander |publisher=BBC News |date=2011-02-17 |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> She argued that Labour must offer radical change to regain the trust of voters, a vision spelt out in ''Scottish Labour New Directions: Change is what we do'',<ref>http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/pdfs/21_03_08_wendy.pdf</ref> a publication outlining her views on the future policy direction for Scottish Labour.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7307371.stm Labour must show radical change] [[BBC]], 23 March 2008</ref> Addressing Labour's Scottish Conference as Leader she spoke of the need for Labour to be the progressive party of Scotland. Alexander argued: \"'Scotland' is not a political philosophy. 'Scotland' can just as easily be [[Adam Smith]] as it can be [[John Smith (Labour Party leader)|John Smith]]. The world over, politics comes down to a choice: right versus left, conservatives versus progressives, nationalists versus internationalists\".<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7319850.stm Alexander says fightback begins] [[BBC]], 29 March 2008</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/pdfs/31_03_08_wendyspeech.pdf Speech to Scottish Conference by Wendy Alexander] [[BBC]], 29 March 2008</ref>\n\nOrganisationally, she called for a new approach to candidate selection, including primary systems to give all Labour supporters a chance to be involved in choosing their local member. Policy initiatives included establishing a Literacy Commission with [[Rhona Brankin]] to investigate child literacy standards in [[Scottish schools]]<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2008/jun/24/schools.education Rebus creator turns government inspector] Guardian, 24 June 2008</ref> (subsequently embraced by all parties in the Parliament),<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/8393805.stm Fifth of Scots have poor literacy] [[BBC]], 4 December 2009</ref> supporting investment in the early years, including nursery places for all vulnerable 2-year-olds, more one-on-one tuition in schools, personalised care plans for those with chronic conditions and legislation providing for a modern apprenticeship for every qualified school leaver who sought one.\n\n===Calman Commission===\n{{main|Calman Commission|Scotland Bill (2011)}}\n\nAlexander made a speech at the [[University of Edinburgh]] on [[St Andrew's Day]] 2007 in which she set out the case for a wide-ranging review of the [[Devolution in the United Kingdom|devolution settlement]], with a view to identifying possible areas for reform.<ref>[http://www.institute-of-governance.org/news-events/news/2007/wendy_alexander_presents_a_new_agenda_for_scotland Wendy Alexander presents A New Agenda for Scotland][http://www.institute-of-governance.org/ Institute of Governance]</ref> The speech laid out her proposals for \"a more balanced [[home rule]] package\" including greater financial [[accountability]] and new tax powers for the [[Scottish Parliament]] (a cause that she had first championed when she led the Allander Series) in order that the \"Union become a more comfortable home for all its members\".<ref>[http://www.heraldscotland.com/alexander-calls-for-tax-powers-to-replace-the-barnett-formula-1.844478 Alexander calls for tax powers to replace the Barnett formula] Herald, 1 December 2007</ref> She said \"Scotland wants to see a future that allows her to walk taller within the UK without walking out\" and called for a new \"expert-led and independent\" Scottish constitutional commission.\n\nAs Labour leader in the Scottish Parliament, she set this in motion by working with the Conservative and Liberal Democrat leaders to set up the [[Commission on Scottish Devolution]] (aka the Calman Commission) in a \"bold cross-party, cross-border initiative\".<ref>[http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/news/Parties-join-forces-to-bulldoze.3587865.jp Parties join forces to bulldoze SNP] Scotsman, 7 December 2007</ref><ref>[http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/politics/it-s-all-part-of-the-process-1.870431 Its all part of the process] Herald, 7 December 2007</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7709850.stm Devolution body to take evidence] [[BBC]]</ref> The review was established by a vote of the Scottish Parliament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7129899.stm |title=MSPs back devolution review body |publisher=BBC News |date=2007-12-06 |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> The Calman Commission became a unique Scottish Parliament-UK Government joint venture which reported back to the Parliament in June 2009 proposing wide-ranging changes in the financing of the Scottish Parliament.<ref>[http://www.commissiononscottishdevolution.org.uk/uploads/2009-06-12-csd-final-report-2009fbookmarked.pdf Serving Scotland Better][[Commission on Scottish Devolution]], June 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.commissiononscottishdevolution.org.uk/uploads/2009-06-12-csd-a5_final-summary_ibook.pdf Serving Scotland Better Executive Summary][[Commission on Scottish Devolution]], June 2009</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/8100215.stm Digesting the Calman report calls] [[BBC]]</ref> Alexander wrote then \"history teaches that constitutional reform has never been gifted to Scotland. It has to be fought and argued for... Calman will shape the next phase of Scotland's journey\u2026[with] a range of common sense measures to improve relationships\".<ref>[http://scotlandonsunday.scotsman.com/opinion/Wendy-Alexander-Blueprint-for-the.5364025.jp Wendy Alexander: Blueprint for the future of Scotland] Scotland on Sunday, 14 June 2009</ref>\n\nOn St. Andrew's Day 2010, three years to the day after Alexander's call for a Commission, the UK Government introduced a new Scotland Bill. The proposals in the bill closely followed the Commission's recommendations and proposed major new financial powers worth \u00a312 billion, giving Holyrood control of a third of its budget. Under the legislation, Holyrood will set a Scottish income tax rate each year from 2015, applying equally to the basic, high and additional rates. The UK Government called it the \"biggest transfer of fiscal powers to Scotland since the creation of the Union.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Brian Taylor |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-11863388 |title=Holyrood to get new budget powers under Scotland Bill |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> In December 2010 Alexander was appointed convener of the Scottish Parliament's Committee to report on the bill.\n\n===Scottish independence referendum===\n{{main|Referendum (Scotland) Bill, 2010}}\n\nDuring a TV interview on 4 May 2008, Wendy Alexander suggested that she would be willing to support a [[referendum]] on [[Scottish Independence]] saying \"Bring it on!\". It was a bold move, but led to suggestions of a rift between her and the prime minister, who did not overtly back her.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-12496030 |title=A look a former Scottish Labour leader Wendy Alexander |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2011-02-17 |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> On 7 May, at [[Prime Minister's Questions]], Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]] stated that she was not, in fact, offering Labour's support for an immediate referendum.<ref>[http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/latestnews/Labour-implodes-over-independence-vote.4061348.jp Labour implodes over independence vote][[The Scotsman]], 8 May 2008</ref>\n\nDuring [[First Minister's Questions]] in the Scottish Parliament, on 8 May, Alexander asked Alex Salmond to bring forward a referendum bill at the first opportunity. [[Alex Salmond]] declined the offer of Labour support for a referendum, preferring to delay by at least a further year, saying \"We will stick to what was laid out in pages 8 and 15 of the SNP manifesto\".<ref>[http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/officialReports/meetingsParliament/or-08/sor0508-02.htm#Col8425 Official Report, 8 May 2008][[Scottish Parliament]]</ref>\n\n== Resignation over foreign donation==\n{{main|Labour party proxy and undeclared donations (2007)}}\n\nIn 2007, a controversy developed after it emerged that Alexander's campaign team had accepted a \u00a3950 impermissible donation from Paul Green, a property magnate,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7479025.stm Q&A: Wendy Alexander donations row ], ''[[BBC]]'', 1 December 2007</ref> a matter that was investigated by the [[Electoral Commission (United Kingdom)|Electoral Commission]] and [[Strathclyde Police]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/7120096.stm Alexander wrote to illegal donor], ''[[BBC News Online]]'', 30 November 2007</ref> When it emerged that the donation of \u00a3950 had come from a personal account, and not a business account, the money was immediately forfeited. Further newspaper reports on 30 November indicated Alexander was aware of the identity of the donor, after having sent a personal letter of gratitude to Mr Green (at his home in [[Jersey]]) concerning the donation.<ref>[http://www.scotsman.com/politics/Bombshell-for-Labour-on-illegal.3585975.jp Bombshell for Labour on illegal donations], ''[[The Scotsman]]'', 1 December 2007</ref> As Mr Green was not registered as an elector in the United Kingdom this barred him from donating to a UK-based party. However, the Electoral Commission concluded in February 2008 that Alexander had taken 'significant steps' to comply with funding regulations and decided there was no basis for further action.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7232516.stm Alexander in clear over donations], ''[[BBC News Online]]'', 7 February 2008</ref> As part of the Electoral Commission ruling, they also stated that Alexander \"did not take all reasonable steps\" and that \"there is not sufficient evidence to establish that an offence has been committed\".<ref>[http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/news-and-media/news-releases/electoral-commission-media-centre/news-releases-donations/statement-by-the-electoral-commission Statement by the Electoral Commission], ''[[Electoral Commission (United Kingdom)|Electoral Commission]]'', 7 February 2008</ref>\nThese mixed messages have resulted in a number of people questioning the decision, including [[Alex Salmond]] the head of the [[Scottish Government]] who likened the result to a ''[[not proven]]'' verdict.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7232516.stm Alexander in clear over donation], ''[[BBC News Online]]'', 7 February 2008</ref>\n\nIn a separate development, a few days earlier in February 2008, the Scottish Parliament standards watchdog reported Alexander to the [[procurator fiscal]] for failing to declare as gifts the donations that were made to the fund for her campaign for the Scottish Labour Party leadership.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7224739.stm Alexander reported over donations], ''[[BBC News Online]]'', 3 February 2008</ref> Alexander had been told by the parliamentary authorities that there was no need to declare these donations as gifts.<ref name=\"Labour leader faces one-day ban\"/> In previous leadership campaigns, campaign donations were not treated as gifts. Again the subsequent investigation led to a decision by the [[Crown Office and Procurator Fiscal Service|Crown Office]] to take no further action.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7281820.stm |title=Alexander will not be prosecuted |publisher=BBC News |date=2008-03-06 |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\nDespite this ruling, on 26 June 2008, on the eve of the Parliamentary summer recess, the SNP-led Standards Committee of the Parliament voted 4 to 3 to propose a one-day ban from the Scottish Parliament<ref name=\"Labour leader faces one-day ban\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7474475.stm |title=Labour leader faces one-day ban |publisher=BBC News |date=2008-06-26 |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> as a sanction for not declaring leadership campaign donations as gifts on the Parliament's register of interests. The proposed ban was overwhelmingly rejected by the Parliament in a subsequent vote in September 2008.<ref>[http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/officialReports/meetingsParliament/or-08/sor0904-02.htm#Col10577 Official Report, Decision Time, 4 September 2008] [[Scottish Parliament]]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7596764.stm |title=MSPs vote against Alexander ban |publisher=BBC News |date=2008-09-04 |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> However, with Holyrood going into summer recess at the time, Alexander would have had to wait until September for all MSPs to vote on the recommendation. So, rather than having the issue hanging over her \u2013 and her party \u2013 Alexander announced her resignation as leader on 28 June 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-12496030 |title=A look at former Scottish Labour leader Wendy Alexander |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2011-02-17 |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> She subsequently stated it had been a mistake for her to take on the leadership of Scottish Labour while her children were so young.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-12496625 |title=Wendy Alexander to quit Scots parliament at election |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nFrom 2008\u20132011 Alexander served as a member of the [[Committees of the Scottish Parliament|Scottish Parliament's Economy, Energy and Tourism Committee]]. She was also convenor of the [[Scotland Bill 2011|Scotland Bill]] Committee, which produced the report for the Scottish Parliament and UK Government in March 2011 proposing [[devolution|new powers]] for the [[Scottish Parliament]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Brian Taylor |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-12621048 |title=MSPs call for more Holyrood power under Scotland Bill |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> Many of these proposals recommend greater [[fiscal autonomy for Scotland]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.scotsman.com/news/The-Wendy-Alexander-plan-aims.6728210.jp |title=The Wendy Alexander plan aims to bridge gap in nation's finances |publisher=News.scotsman.com |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> including improved borrowing powers, the ability to issue bonds and further tax devolution.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-11863392 |title=Q&A: Scotland Bill |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2010-11-30 |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> Despite the Scottish Government's initial opposition to the bill they supported the Scotland Bill Committee's recommendations, with parliament voting 121:3 in favour. In her valedictory speech on the Scotland Bill, Alexander said: \"This initiative has from beginning to end been cross-party, consensual and co-operative among the participating parties. [...] The bill will deliver the most far-reaching transfer of financial powers from London since the creation of the union. [...] In the future, all Scottish political parties will have to make decisions about raising money as well as about spending it. [...] The bill serves Scotland better [...] It is, quite simply, in the national interest.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/apps2/business/orsearch/ReportView.aspx?r=6175&mode=html |title=Official Report \u2013 Meeting of the Parliament 10 March 2011 |publisher=Scottish.parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\nShe stood down from Parliament in May 2011 to seek a new life outside active politics.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-12496030 |title=A Look at former Scottish Labour leader Wendy Alexander |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2011-02-17 |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\nAlexander also serves as a member of the [[Social Market Foundation]]'s Advisory Board and [[Reform Scotland]]'s Political Advisory Board.\n\n==Personal life and family==\nWendy Alexander is married to Professor Brian Ashcroft and has [[Twin|fraternal twin]] children.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAlexander's brother [[Douglas Alexander|Douglas]], was the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] Member of Parliament for [[Paisley and Renfrewshire South (UK Parliament constituency)|Paisley and Renfrewshire South]] and was previously [[Secretary of State for International Development]] and [[Secretary of State for Scotland]]. He served as Shadow Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs under Labour Party Leader [[Ed Miliband]], and lost his seat at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] to 20-year old [[Mhairi Black]] of the [[Scottish National Party|SNP]].\n\nAlexander supports [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers FC]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/rangers-celebrity-supporters-out-in-force-976295|title=Rangers' celebrity supporters out in force for UEFA Cup final|work=Daily Record|date=3 May 2008|accessdate=3 May 2008|location=Glasgow|first=John|last=Ferguson}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Scottish Executive Ministerial Teams]]\n* [[Scotland Bill 2010-11]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/msp/membersPages/wendy_alexander/index.htm Scottish Parliament biography]\n*[http://www.wendyalexandermsp.org.uk/ Wendy Alexander MSP]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par | sct}}\n|-\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency created }}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Member of the Scottish Parliament]] for [[Paisley North (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Paisley North]] | years=[[1999 Scottish Parliament election|1999]]\u20132011 }}\n{{s-after|after=Constituency abolished}}\n{{s-off}}\n|-\n{{s-non | reason = Office created }}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Minister for Communities and Sport|Minister for Communities]] | years = 1999\u20132000 }}\n{{s-non | reason = Office abolished }}\n|-\n{{s-bef | before = [[Henry McLeish]] }}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[Minister for Enterprise 